By 1989 there were only five state travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recreation and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies sold mainly trips to the socialist East Block countries, and in the West, only electors were allowed at that time.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Peninsula Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-western course and therefore the journey to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed to travel freely in the context of socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he would need a so-called letter of invitation, otherwise individual trips would not be possible.
At that time, the travel offices also offered trips to the west, but then they had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag before the travel office, or at least have \"good acquaintances\" in the travel office.
