Asphalt from UNAM prevents stroke holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM developed with polymers modified asphalte to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
Would it not be necessary to repair almost 200,000 holes if the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the Valley of Mexico) broke out, Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warned and assured that if the layout and maintenance of the Asphalt Laag were deemed appropriate, the number of holes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture “Slagholes from a technical point of view” which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory, which he is responsible for, developed modified asphalte with polymers, to produce a mixture similar to the Asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance both at high and low temperatures.
Mr. Nájera said this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, in order to improve the behavior of the road burden and thus avoid the occurrence of hit holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound of which some of it has a high molecular weight - the so-called aspholds - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes. Together, they give the road burden its characteristic toelastic behavior.
Tehelastic behavior of the Asphalt means that it behaves at high temperatures of almost 180° C. like a liquid, at 120° C. it is very delicate and at 50° C. it is almost fixed, while it is broken at very low temperatures.
“This means that the resistance of the Asphalt on the streets is not uniform, but is changing one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations,” the chemical engineer said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City had mostly a flexible road burden composed of six layers of material, the last of which included three asphalts.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer made of asphalt, which is made of small, asphalted stones and then solidified stones.
Each individual stone of this wearing layer, has been coated in Asphalt.
If the vehicles are moving on and forces are generated, this layer allows for good power distribution in the street area.
“If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed,” said the chemical engineer.
“On the wear layer,” he said, “a last layer is laid out, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. of sand, which has also been grounded in Asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they need to produce friction.
Those of this street light receive and distribute most of the forces, the support layer also needs an adequate thickness and the material from which it consists must be maintained.
The weather conditions, in particular moisture and temperature fluctuations, are other factors to be considered, above all, the water, he said, “because it significantly affects the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain is moistened, water penetrates the layer and only occurs hard again. This causes a wave of all the layers of the road cover and as a result the appearance of impact holes.
When a impact hole arises, he said, “the cover layer is first worn off, while the wear layer is only affected after that. But the damage does not occur immediately, but is a process that has to be maintained in the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs.”
The member in the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of shock holes, which is why the thickness of each layer of the road load should always be in relation to the vehicle load and it should be ensured that this regulation is followed to avoid frequent impact holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that many other research works were still waiting, for example, on Asphaltemulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the shock holes could be repaired simply and without application high temperatures.
